Feature: the pin bump is committed to the bc-launcher repo so each rebuild is traceable to the dependency version that triggered it

  Pins ADR-022 D2 step 3 — the workflow "rebuilds bc-base and republishes
  :latest at the new digest (and commits the bumped Dockerfile, so the pins
  stay content-addressable per scenario 37's reproducibility property)." This
  scenario pins that the bump is not an ephemeral in-run edit: the mutated
  docker/bc-base/Dockerfile is committed back to the shopsystem-bc-launcher
  repository, so the committed Dockerfile records exactly the dependency
  version that the republished bc-base:latest was built from — making the
  rebuild traceable to its triggering release. A workflow that builds from an
  in-memory or working-tree-only pin bump without committing the bumped
  Dockerfile must FAIL this scenario. (Targets shopsystem-bc-launcher.)

  Note (ADR-022 scope): ADR-022 D2 names "commits the bumped Dockerfile" but
  does not decide whether the rebuild is additionally tagged. This scenario
  therefore pins the COMMIT-of-the-bump property that ADR-022 decided and does
  not assert a separate version-tag-on-rebuild behavior ADR-022 left to D1's
  existing v* publish path (scenario 37).

  @scenario_hash:2b69c3b682f7871d
  Scenario: when the workflow bumps a pin and rebuilds, it commits the bumped Dockerfile recording the triggering dependency version
    Given the centralized scheduled workflow bumps a baked dependency pin in "docker/bc-base/Dockerfile" from "@v1.0.0" to "@v1.1.0"
    When the workflow rebuilds bc-base and republishes "ghcr.io/dstengle/shopsystem-bc-base:latest" from that bumped Dockerfile
    Then the bumped "docker/bc-base/Dockerfile" is committed back to the shopsystem-bc-launcher repository
    And the committed Dockerfile records the dependency pinned at "@v1.1.0" that the republished bc-base:latest was built from
    And the build was not produced from an uncommitted working-tree-only pin edit
